        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-23T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-23T12:00:00-05:00" n="692"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d692">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.01/10–2344: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Representative to the Provisional Government of
                        the French Republic at Paris</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="95" xml:id="d692fn95">Jefferson Caffery was confirmed by
                        the Senate as Ambassador to France, November 25, 1944.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-23T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 23, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 23—2:29 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>132. For the Secretary, Under Secretary, Dunn, and Matthews. At 5 p.m. local time
                    (noon Washington) I and my British, Russian <pb facs="0760" n="748"
                        xml:id="pg_748"/> and Canadian colleagues called on Bidault and handed him
                    our letters extending recognition to the French administration as Provisional
                    Government France (we all made a few appropriate remarks. Bidault who was much
                    moved replied in a dignified manner stressing the importance of getting on with
                    the war and emphasizing the hope that France would increase her part therein).
                    He added that the French Government recognized my colleagues and myself in our
                    ambassadorial capacity; no further agreement was necessary he added.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
